40|$|In this paper, {{we address}} the issue of {{resistance}} as the attempt of local political discourses to maintain their autonomy within larger discourses. We are interested in how local discourses can maintain a partial segregation in respect to specific issue fields. What we are interested in is how discourse changes by shifting from lower to higher levels of locality. We do so by analysing discourses in the context of European <b>cohesion</b> <b>policies.</b> <b>Cohesion</b> <b>policies</b> utilize more than one third of the budget of the European Union to facilitate the converge of economic development of European regions. Overall, this research setting allows to investigating how discourse on <b>cohesion</b> <b>policies</b> modifies as it shifts from national to regional media. We investigate how at regional level the discourse is innervated by idiosyncratic topics that reflect contextual framing and interest structures. Empirically, our work addresses a key concern: how it is possible that awareness of such an important financial effort by EU is so low especially in the regions that benefit the most from the programme...|$|R
40|$|Abstract:On May 1 st 2004, 10 Central and Eastern European (CEE) {{countries}} {{joined the}} EU and became fully eligible for communitarian financial support. While {{the conditions for}} eligibility are the same, at regional level CEE territories are provided with very different socioeconomic settings. In particular, different regions are differently endowed with what has been labelled ‘territorial capital’, so that the endowment of public and private, material and immaterial assets significantly varies across regions, including infrastructure, private capital, human and social capital. This set of territorial conditions, enabling economic development to take place, is here assumed to impact the outcome of <b>cohesion</b> <b>policies</b> as well. This paper is hence aimed at assessing the role of specific territorial conditions on the efficient implementation of <b>cohesion</b> <b>policies</b> in CEE NUTS 3 regions. The analysis points out the mechanisms through which the endowment of specific territorial assets affects the outcome of <b>Cohesion</b> <b>policies.</b> It appears that for {{a large number of}} territorial capital assets, increasing returns are present and regions more endowed with specific types of territorial capital are more able to gain from policy investment in related fields...|$|R
